First, let's find the symmetric difference of sets A and B. The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection. 

A ∆ B = (A - B) ∪ (B - A)

A - B = {4, 6, 8, 10}
B - A = {3, 5, 7, 11}

A ∆ B = {3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11}

Now, let's find the intersection of the resulting set (A ∆ B) with set A.

(A ∆ B) ∩ A = {4, 6, 8, 10}

Next, let's find the symmetric difference of sets B and A.

B ∆ A = (B - A) ∪ (A - B)

B - A = {3, 5, 7, 11}
A - B = {4, 6, 8, 10}

B ∆ A = {3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11}

Now, let's find the intersection of the resulting set (B ∆ A) with set A.

(B ∆ A) ∩ A = {4, 6, 8, 10}

We can see that the symmetric difference of sets A and B is commutative with respect to intersection, as (A ∆ B) ∩ A = (B ∆ A) ∩ A = {4, 6, 8, 10}.
